John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
Scotland’s independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence. This continued with further outstanding exam results in 2018 and is only underpinned by individual and shared successes in the fields of sports, art, music and other joint ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide their students and their parents with the highest possible level of care.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and sought after in schools as elective subjects.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart."
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The current results of this year's exam show that languages with the highest existing rates are at the top of the independent school rankings.
A total of 68 percent of the students who learned foreign languages achieved grade A at the higher examinations.
The data collected by 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 per cent of Mandarin students achieved grade A at the higher examinations, while 72 per cent of German learners also achieved grade A at the higher examinations, 69 per cent of French learners and 63 per cent of Spanish learners.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now regarded as elective subjects as well as STEM subjects (natural sciences, engineering, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons that employers gave for the problems of filling vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
As more and more vacancies require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future through such a lifelong ability.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people a lead over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for the children of today that we now invest in language lessons.
Children who speak several languages, in particular languages from developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught at all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more traditional modern languages, while other languages that are considered most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese, will teach.
Wherever your child's interests lie, in independent schools, there will always be a number of languages to choose from with suitably specialised teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares the children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future looks like.
At this time in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country, which is why this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be regarded as "international communication capacity."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
