North Korea's Secretary of State told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and that under these circumstances the country would not unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the World Organization that North Korea last year had "good will to take substantial action", for example stopping nuclear and missile testing, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing itself not to multiply nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we do not see any response from the US," he said.
"Without confidence in the US, there is no confidence in our national security, and under these circumstances, we will by no means disarm ourselves unilaterally first."
While Ri repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phase-wise" approach to denuclearization, where North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a US President-in-Office and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim had promised to work towards the "denuclearisation of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea is aiming for an official end to the Korean war between 1950 and 1953, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington also opposes calls for a relaxation of the strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US insists on "first denuclearization" and increases the pressure of sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and even opposes the "declaration of the end of the war," said Ri.
“The assumption that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a fantasy of people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust."
Ri did not respond to plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US head of state had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If South Korea were the other party in the question of denuclearization instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to a standstill."
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech differed enormously from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target North Korea's missiles on the US mainland after "the evil president" Trump Kim had called "the rocket man" on suicide mission.
This year Trump, who had threatened last year with the "total destruction" of North Korea, heaped praise on Kim at the United Nations for his courage with regard to disarmament steps. However, he said that much work was still to be done and that the sanctions had to remain in force until North Korea's denuclearisation.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it: "Whether it takes two years, three years or five months doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
