Harvard students learn to sleep enough in one class
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all students in basic studies get more sleep this year. This is a measure against the expanding macho culture of keeping up with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unneeded when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and in his opinion is the first such course in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why do I find out about this only now, in my last year?’
According to her words, no one had ever told her how important sleep was. That surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year's first course explained to students how the basics of good sleeping habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the University's health services, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In a section, the students see the picture of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books. They get information about the effect of caffeine and light as well as the effects of lack of sleep on the athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
They are then encouraged to think about their daily routine using a map of the university campus with interactive symbols.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health," added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of pushing a "night shift" is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Ensuring sufficient good sleep should be the "secret weapon" of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said. Moreover, weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course. He had taken one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that, in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study programme before starting their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler, students should set an alarm clock for bedtime and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light", which can be triggered by electronic screens and LED lighting, and can break the circadian rhythm, leading to problems when they fall asleep.
